*   **Stoichiometric and structure variants:** While we think of NaCl as a 1:1 ratio, scientists have discovered other sodium-chloride compounds with different [stoichiometries](/Stoichiometry) under extreme conditions. Na₃Cl, Na₂Cl, Na₃Cl₂, NaCl₃, and NaCl₇. &#91;34&#93; Even hexagonal NaCl has been observed. &#91;35&#93; It seems even the simplest systems can surprise you, given the right pressure.

***

#### Occurrence

It’s everywhere. In the [Earth's crust](/Earth%27s_crust) as [halite](/Halite). Suspended in the atmosphere as [sea salt](/Sea_salt) particles. These particles are crucial [cloud condensation nuclei](/Cloud_condensation_nuclei) over the oceans, enabling [cloud](/Cloud) formation in otherwise pristine [air](/Air). &#91;36&#93; &#91;37&#93; It's a fundamental part of the planet's processes.

***

#### Production

It’s [mass-produced](/Mass_production) through [evaporation](/Evaporation) of [seawater](/Seawater) or [brine](/Brine) from [brine wells](/Brine_well) and [salt lakes](/Salt_lake_(geography)). [Mining](/Salt_mine) is also significant. China leads the world in production. In 2017, global production was around 280 million tonnes, with the US, India, Germany, and Canada following. &#91;38&#93; It’s even a byproduct of [potassium](/Potassium) mining.

The images speak for themselves: modern mines, vast evaporation ponds on the [Dead Sea](/Dead_Sea), and endless salt flats in [Bolivia](/Bolivia). It’s a global commodity.

